To evaluate the effective delivery and control release of the carrier, release kinetics models including zero order, first order, Weibull, Higuchi models, and so on, are exploited to predict drug release in vitro [18]. These models mainly rely on the diffusion equations. Ritger-Peppas equation (Q = kPt
                        n
                     ) is usually used to analyze the release mechanism. In this equation, n is the release index, when n is less than 0.45 corresponding to Fick diffusion, when 0.45 ≤ n ≤ 0.89 corresponding to non-Fick diffusion (drug diffusion and matrix dissolution), and n is more than 0.89 to case II transport (skeleton dissolution) [19]. Employing zero-order, first-order, Higuchi and Korsmeyer-Peppas models, Zhang groups studied the release behaviors of the collagen (COL)/bacterial cellulose (BC) porous microspheres using bovine serum albumin (BSA) as the model protein, and found that BSA conformed to the first-order release model and BSA was mainly adsorbed to the inner wall of the pores in the microsphere [19]. Park and Kim studied drug (BTZ) release from a hydrogel using mathematical models, and reported it fitted first order model and followed non-Fickian diffusion [20].

In Eq. (1), Yu
                         (Ys
                        ) is the quantum yield of CDs (standard), Fu
                         (Fs
                        ) is the integrated area of the CDs’ (standard’s) emission spectrum, Au
                         (As
                        ) is the absorbance at the excitation wavelength of CDs (standard), respectively.

The prepared CDs were characterized by TEM, DLS, zeta potential, UV, FL, FI-IR, XRD, 13C NMR (Fig. 1
                        ) and XPS (Fig. 2
                        ). Fig. 1A showed the TEM image of CDs, in which the particles were spherical morphology with the diameter about 5 nm (Fig. 1A), which was consistent with the hydrodynamic size (about 4 ~ 5 nm) measured by dynamic light scattering (DLS, Fig. 1B) through Nano-ZS90. Particles with a high ζ potential are self-stabilizing, due to their charge inhibits coalescence and enhances stability [16,17]. In general, the particles are stable when the absolute value of the ζ potential is about 30 mV [25]. The zeta potential of the prepared CDs was −28.3 mV (Fig. 1C), so the CDs were stable in solution.

CDs-DOX was prepared successfully and characterized by ζ potential, UV–vis spectra and FL spectra. Fig. 3
                        A showed that the optimal mass ratio of CDs and DOX (m/m) was 1:2 and the drug loading was 37.2%. Fig. 3B was the zeta potential of CDs, DOX and CDs-DOX. CDs were synthesized with the negative zeta potential of −28.3 mV. The zeta potential of free DOX was 12.0 mV and that of CDs-DOX was −3.27 mV, respectively. It indicated that the electrostatic interaction existed between CDs and DOX, due to the electronegative of CDs and electropositive of DOX, although CDs also could conjugate with DOX by covalent bonding through the –NH2 (on CDs) and –C=O (on DOX) (Scheme 1
                        ).
